=========================================================
NEW AND DELETE IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
new:
Allocates memory dynamically on the Heap and optionally initializes it.

delete:
Releases dynamically allocated memory from the Heap.

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED DYNAMIC MEMORY ALLOCATION?
=========================================================

Used when:
• Size is known only at runtime
• Object lifetime must extend beyond function scope
• Large objects need to be allocated
• Dynamic data structures (Linked List, Tree, Graph)

=========================================================
SYNTAX OF NEW
=========================================================

datatype* ptr = new datatype;

Example:

int* ptr = new int;

=========================================================
MEMORY DIAGRAM
=========================================================

int* ptr = new int(10);

Stack                Heap
------               ------
ptr ------------->   [10]

ptr itself is on Stack.
Allocated integer is on Heap.

=========================================================
INITIALIZATION USING NEW
=========================================================

int* p1 = new int;
int* p2 = new int();
int* p3 = new int(10);

---------------------------------------------------------
Statement                 Value
---------------------------------------------------------
new int                   Garbage Value
new int()                 0
new int(10)               10

=========================================================
DYNAMIC ARRAY ALLOCATION
=========================================================

int n = 5;

int* arr = new int[n];

Memory:

arr ---> [ ][ ][ ][ ][ ]

=========================================================
INITIALIZE DYNAMIC ARRAY
=========================================================

int* arr = new int[5]();

All elements initialized to:

0

=========================================================
DELETE
=========================================================

delete ptr;

Frees memory allocated by:

new

Example:

int* ptr = new int(10);

delete ptr;

=========================================================
DELETE FOR ARRAYS
=========================================================

delete[] arr;

Example:

int* arr = new int[5];

delete[] arr;

=========================================================
VERY IMPORTANT
=========================================================

new
     ↔
delete

new[]
     ↔
delete[]

Never mix them.

Wrong:

int* arr = new int[5];

delete arr;       // Undefined Behavior

Correct:

delete[] arr;

=========================================================
WHAT DOES NEW DO INTERNALLY?
=========================================================

new performs TWO operations:

1. Allocates memory
2. Calls constructor

Example:

Test* ptr = new Test();

Steps:

1. Allocate memory on Heap
2. Call constructor
3. Return pointer

=========================================================
WHAT DOES DELETE DO INTERNALLY?
=========================================================

delete performs TWO operations:

1. Calls destructor
2. Releases memory

Example:

delete ptr;

Steps:

1. Destructor called
2. Memory freed

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    Test()
    {
        cout << "Constructor\n";
    }

    ~Test()
    {
        cout << "Destructor\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Test* ptr = new Test();

    delete ptr;
}

Output:

Constructor
Destructor

=========================================================
NEW WITH OBJECTS
=========================================================

class Test
{
};

Test* ptr = new Test();

delete ptr;

=========================================================
DYNAMIC ARRAY OF OBJECTS
=========================================================

Test* ptr = new Test[3];

delete[] ptr;

Constructor called:

3 times.

Destructor called:

3 times.

=========================================================
MEMORY LEAK
=========================================================

Definition:
Allocated memory becomes inaccessible.

Example:

int* ptr = new int(10);

ptr = nullptr;

Memory lost.

Leak occurred.

=========================================================
CORRECT WAY
=========================================================

delete ptr;
ptr = nullptr;

=========================================================
DANGLING POINTER
=========================================================

int* ptr = new int(10);

delete ptr;

cout << *ptr;      // Undefined Behavior

ptr points to freed memory.

Solution:

delete ptr;
ptr = nullptr;

=========================================================
malloc() - C INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================================

What is malloc()?
-----------------
malloc (Memory Allocation) is used to dynamically allocate memory at runtime from the heap.

Header File:
-------------
#include <stdlib.h>

Syntax:
-------
ptr = (type*)malloc(n * sizeof(type));

Example:
--------
int *ptr = (int*)malloc(5 * sizeof(int));

Allocates memory for 5 integers.

---------------------------------------------------------

Key Points
----------
1. Allocates memory on the heap.
2. Memory is uninitialized (contains garbage values).
3. Returns a void* pointer.
4. Must be typecast in C++.
5. Returns NULL if allocation fails.
6. Memory must be released using free().
7. Size is specified in bytes.

---------------------------------------------------------

Example
-------

int *ptr = (int*)malloc(5 * sizeof(int));

if(ptr == NULL)
{
    cout << "Allocation failed";
}
else
{
    ptr[0] = 10;
}

free(ptr);
ptr = nullptr;

---------------------------------------------------------

malloc vs new
--------------

malloc()
---------
• C function
• Allocates memory only
• Does NOT call constructor
• Returns void*
• Free using free()

new
----
• C++ operator
• Allocates memory + calls constructor
• Returns typed pointer
• Free using delete

---------------------------------------------------------

Common Interview Questions
--------------------------
Q. Where is malloc memory allocated?
Ans: Heap.

Q. Does malloc initialize memory?
Ans: No. Memory contains garbage values.

Q. What does malloc return?
Ans: void* (NULL on failure).

Q. Which header file contains malloc()?
Ans: <stdlib.h>

Q. How do you free malloc memory?
Ans: free(ptr);

Q. Can malloc allocate objects?
Ans: Yes, but constructors are NOT called. In C++, prefer new.

Q. What happens if you forget free()?
Ans: Memory leak.

Q. Is malloc used in Modern C++?
Ans: Rarely. Prefer new, smart pointers, or STL containers.

---------------------------------------------------------

Best Practices
--------------
✓ Always check for NULL.
✓ Always free allocated memory.
✓ Set pointer to nullptr after free().
✓ Prefer new/delete or smart pointers in C++.
✓ Use std::vector instead of malloc for arrays in Modern C++.

