=========================================================
PLACEMENT NEW (SHORT INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
Placement new constructs an object in pre-allocated memory.
It does NOT allocate memory.

Syntax:
new(memory_address) Type(arguments);

Example:

char buffer[sizeof(int)];
int* ptr = new(buffer) int(10);

Key Points:
• Uses existing memory.
• Does NOT allocate heap memory.
• Calls constructor only.
• delete cannot be used.
• Destructor must be called manually for class objects.

Used In:
• Memory pools
• STL allocators
• Embedded systems
• Shared memory
• Game engines
• High-performance applications

Normal new vs Placement new

new
• Allocates memory + calls constructor.

Placement new
• Uses existing memory + calls constructor only.

Interview One-liner:
Placement new constructs an object at a specified memory location without allocating new memory.
