What is operator new()?
=========================================================

operator new() is a low-level function that allocates raw memory only.

It:
• Allocates memory from the heap.
• Returns a void* pointer.
• Does NOT call constructors.
• Does NOT create an object.

Example:

void* mem = operator new(sizeof(int));

Only memory is allocated.

To construct an object in that memory, placement new is required.

Example:

new(mem) int(10);

---------------------------------------------------------

Normal new internally performs:

1. operator new(sizeof(T));    // Allocate raw memory
2. Placement new               // Call constructor
3. Return typed pointer

---------------------------------------------------------

Interview One-liner:

operator new() only allocates raw memory. It does not construct an object or call the constructor.
The new operator uses operator new() internally and then constructs the object.
